How Mining Works=C2=A0
It is said that prostitution is the oldest profession, but mining was alrea=
dy 41,000 years old when prostitution was still in diapers.=C2=A0
The Ngwenya Mine, located in the western part of Eswatini (formerly known a=
s Swaziland), is considered the world=E2=80=99s oldest known mining site. R=
adiocarbon dating of charcoal found in its mine shafts suggests humans bega=
n mining the site 43,000 years ago.=C2=A0
Early Man used stones and animal horns to dig shallow pits and extract spec=
ular haematite from Ngwenya for use in cosmetics and rituals. The industry =
has expanded and matured since then, but at its core, the mining remains th=
e process of extracting valuable minerals and metals from the earth.
Just what we pulled from the earth, and how we were able to process it, has=
 been so important to human progress that it=E2=80=99s defined ages.=C2=A0
During the Neolithic period, or Stone Age, early humans mined flint and sto=
nes for use in tools and weapons. The Chalcolithic period, or Copper Age, b=
egan around 5500 BCE with the discovery of copper and its use in tools and =
weapons, and the Bronze Age kicked off roughly two millennia later as human=
s discovered tin and realized it could be alloyed with copper to create a h=
arder and more durable metal. Another two millennia later, the invention of=
 Bloomery smelting [ https://substack.com/redirect/399b93b0-7f3b-4084-9b14-=
1fb20a6f7323?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8Exk=
RNpU ] brought humanity into the Iron Age. And while we stopped naming ages=
 after metals thereafter, our ability to discover, alloy, and use new metal=
s has paced our progress. The Bessemer and Hall H=C3=A9roult processes, whi=
ch I wrote about in The Techno-Industrial Revolution [ https://substack.com=
/redirect/76a92edb-cddf-41a0-acb0-1790aa94fcf2?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5=
T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ], shaped the Industrial Revolution =
by making Steel and Aluminium, respectively, cheap and abundant.=C2=A0
Through most of those ages, humans mined like the ancient Eswatinians, usin=
g their muscles and simple tools to extract materials close to earth=E2=80=
=99s surface. But each new discovery, combined with human creativity, led t=
o the next. New discoveries unlocked not just new levels of human civilizat=
ion, but new ways to mine and make even more metals.=C2=A0
Mining=E2=80=99s progression has been an evolution, but if you had to pick =
a date for the birth of modern mining, you might pick 1867, when Alfred Nob=
el, the Nobel Prize guy, discovered dynamite.=C2=A0
Dynamite let miners blast through hard rock safely and efficiently to acces=
s deposits that were previously too difficult to mine, made mining operatio=
ns more economically viable, and enabled the expansion of mining across the=
 earth into new areas and further beneath the earth into deeper shafts and =
tunnels with richer deposits.=C2=A0
This is a pattern that has played out across the history of mining. I=E2=80=
=99m admittedly new to the space, but it appears that this cycle that plays=
 out over and over again:=C2=A0
Discovery and exploitation of easily accessible deposits: Miners identify a=
nd extract resources from deposits that are relatively easy to find and min=
e using existing technologies and methods.
Depletion of easily accessible deposits: As the most accessible deposits ar=
e exhausted, miners face increasing challenges in finding and extracting ne=
w resources economically.
Technological and process innovations: To overcome these challenges, the mi=
ning industry develops new technologies, techniques, and processes that ena=
ble miners to discover new deposits, access harder-to-reach resources, and =
improve the efficiency of extraction and processing.
Expansion into new frontiers: Armed with these innovations, miners can expl=
ore and exploit previously inaccessible or uneconomical deposits, expanding=
 the scope of mining operations and adding to the available resource base.
Repeat
A more familiar example of the same concept from the oil and gas industry m=
ay be fracking. A couple of decades ago, the world worried that we were abo=
ut to reach peak oil, after which we would begin running out of black gold.=
 That has not happened. It turns out that we weren=E2=80=99t approaching pe=
ak oil, but the peak in oil we could extract profitably using the industry=
=E2=80=99s then state-of-the-art methods.=C2=A0
Same thing here. We are not running out of metals and minerals, despite the=
 decline in new discoveries, but of metals and minerals that we can identif=
y and extract profitably. Now, as always, creative people will invent new t=
echnological solutions to remedy the situation. Earth AI is one of the comp=
anies doing that on the exploration side, and there are others on the minin=
g side, including startups automating mining equipment and ore-sorting, and=
 others, like KoBold, finding new deposits on existing minesites.=C2=A0
All of the innovation comes back to discovering and mining deposits profita=
bly. To understand which types of deposits miners might want to buy, then, =
we need to understand the economics of a mine.=C2=A0
Mine Economics=C2=A0
If you understand the economics of a mine and the factors that influence it=
s profitability, you can skip this section. For the rest of us, you can thi=
nk of the basic business equation of a mine as something like:=C2=A0
Profit =3D Price of Metal x Amount Mined - CapEx - OpEx - Refining & Proces=
sing Costs
Price of Metal: these are commodities, and the price is set by the global m=
arket.=C2=A0
Amount Mined: how much of the metal are you pulling up in a given time peri=
od.
CapEx: includes the costs of exploring, developing, and constructing the mi=
ne, amortized over the life of the mine.=C2=A0
OpEx: expenses to run the mine, including labor, energy, materials, equipme=
nt maintenance, and logistics to get the metals to market.=C2=A0
Refining=C2=A0 & Processing Costs: turning the raw material into marketable=
 form by separating and purifying the valuable metals from the rock and dir=
t it comes up in.=C2=A0
The price of the metal is somewhat out of the miner=E2=80=99s control, alth=
ough miners can choose to sit on deposits until prices rise to the point at=
 which it becomes profitable to mine it. Everything else is within the cont=
rol of the miner, and miners choose to mine deposits based on a number of f=
actors that impact their profitability.=C2=A0
Those factors include:
Size of the Deposit: The volume or tonnage of the ore body is crucial becau=
se it determines the life of the mine and economies of scale, and thus how =
much capital the miner can invest in the site. Explorers and developers det=
ermine this by drilling a lot of holes increasingly far from the initial ho=
le to determine how wide and deep the deposit is during feasibility, and mi=
ners confirm this with their own team of geologists.=C2=A0
Grade of Ore: This is the concentration of the valuable mineral or metal wi=
thin the ore, typically measured as a percentage or in grams per ton (g/t).=
 Higher grades are better, because they reduce OpEx, refining and processin=
g costs, and environmental impact.=C2=A0
Depth of Deposit: Shallow deposits are generally cheaper and safer to mine,=
 often suitable for open-pit mining. Deep deposits require more complex and=
 expensive underground mining techniques, increasing CapEx and OpEx.
Accessibility and Infrastructure: Proximity to roads, power sources, and po=
rts reduces transportation and energy costs. Remote locations typically mea=
n the miner has to run their own roads and power, increasing CapEx and OpEx=
=2E The Biden Administration is spendin=
g $2.3 billion on an African railway [=
 https://substack.com/redirect/18ca28cc-8a85-48a0-ab2b-27e4c3e0a536?j=3DeyJ=
1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] to get critic=
al metals out of Zambia.=C2=A0
Political, Regulatory, and Environmental: Political stability is crucial to=
 the long-term viability of a mine; you don=E2=80=99t want to spend hundred=
s of millions of dollars only to have a new regime kick you out of their co=
untry. Getting permits and approvals can be more or less expensive, time-co=
nsuming, and existential depending on the environmental impact and local re=
gulatory environment.=C2=A0
Capital: These are expensive projects that often require dedicated project =
financing, and the cost (and availability) of capital is a key lever on pro=
fitability.=C2=A0
Whew. I just threw a lot at you, but each thing I listed is crucial to unde=
rstanding whether a mine will be profitable, and therefore, how valuable a =
given discovery might be for a company like Earth AI. The ideal discovery i=
s a large, high-grade deposit, close to the surface, in a politically stabl=
e and regulatorily friendly locale with easy access to infrastructure.=C2=
=A0
Some challenges facing less-than-ideal deposits are being addressed by tech=
nology: methods to dig deeper more cheaply, automation, and better processi=
ng and refining. But the easiest way to make a mine profitable is just to d=
iscover more ideal mines and prove more quickly that they=E2=80=99re ideal,=
 which is where Earth AI is focusing.
Earth AI is an Explorer. Understanding where that fits into the mining indu=
stry value chain is the last bit of mining background we=E2=80=99ll need to=
 dig into before we get to the Earth AI story.=C2=A0
The Structure of the Mining Industry=C2=A0
Like the pharma industry, mining features different types of companies that=
 operate at different stages in the development cycle, and often work with,=
 or sell to, each other. There are three main categories of companies:
Explorers: Like wildcatters for metal, they focus on discovering and explor=
ing new mineral deposits. Their goal is to identify promising mineral depos=
its and then either sell the property or partner with larger mining compani=
es to develop the resource.=C2=A0
Developers: These companies have identified a mineral deposit and are worki=
ng on developing it into a mine. They may be in the process of securing per=
mits, financing, and constructing the necessary infrastructure to begin min=
ing operations.
Producers: These are mining companies with anywhere from one to multiple op=
erating mines generating revenue. Mid-Tier Producers might operate one or a=
 few mines, and focus on a particular region or metal. Major Producers are =
global, operating tens of mines across a diverse portfolio of assets, and c=
an reach market capitalizations exceeding $10 or even $100 billion. Example=
s include companies like BHP, Rio Tinto, and Vale.=C2=A0
There is also a flotilla of ancillary companies that supports the industry =
with tools, services, and money.=C2=A0
Royalty and Streaming Companies provide financing to mining companies in ex=
change for a share of the revenue or a portion of the mineral production fr=
om the mine. Many explorers, developers, and producers hire external Drilli=
ng Contractors to dig holes, collect samples, and dig the mine. Mining Cons=
ultants assist with geology, planning, environmental management and feasibi=
lity studies. Mining Equipment Manufacturers like Caterpillar and Komatsu m=
ake the drills, excavators, haul trucks, and processing plants. There are e=
ven dedicated Explosives Suppliers like Orica and Dyno Nobel that provide t=
he explosives and blasting services necessary to go deep or through hard ro=
ck. Software providers, environmental and social impact assessment consulta=
nts, waste management companies, logistics and transportation providers, an=
d mining safety and training providers all support the effort.=C2=A0
But in terms of actually finding new deposits and getting them out of the g=
round and into the market, those three categories are the big ones.=C2=A0
Often, the same company can play multiple roles. An explorer might become a=
 developer once they make their discovery, and may even hold on all the way=
 to becoming a producer.=C2=A0
Pretium Resources began as an explorer for gold deposits in British Columbi=
a, discovered the Brucejack mine, developed it, sold a 4.8% stake to Newcre=
st Mining, and then sold the remaining shares to Newcrest for $2.8 billion =
in 2022.=C2=A0=C2=A0
Just as often, explorers make a discovery and flip a stake to a developer, =
which handles resource definition and feasibility, and may even start to pl=
an construction on the mine, before flipping it to a producer.=C2=A0
Because the same company can play multiple roles, another way you might see=
 the industry broken down is into three categories based on size: Juniors, =
Intermediates, and Seniors.=C2=A0
Juniors are typically explorers and may do a little development. They try t=
o make discoveries, which they can develop themselves or sell to larger pla=
yers.=C2=A0
Intermediates have advanced beyond the exploration stage, and typically hav=
e at least one operating mine. They make revenue from production, but aren=
=E2=80=99t as large as Seniors. Often, they=E2=80=99re focused on one regio=
n or type of metal. To grow, they might focus on expanding their existing o=
perations or acquiring new deposits.=C2=A0
Seniors are the largest mining companies, with multiple operating mines acr=
oss the globe and significant production capacity. They engage in all activ=
ities: exploration, development, and production, and also expand by making =
new discoveries at existing minesites or acquiring new projects to expand.
However you break it down, this globe-spanning enterprise produced [ https:=
//substack.com/redirect/92ab3d92-7500-45e0-b224-cfd15881e641?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOX=
AwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] almost 2.2 billion t=
onnes of metal in 2022, nearly 90% of which was iron.
But as discussed earlier, while production from operating mines has been st=
eadily increasing, discovery of new mines has been on the decline.=C2=A0
That=E2=80=99s the problem that Roman Teslyuk set out to solve.=C2=A0
