The Biotech Platform Business Model
Earth AI=E2=80=99s business model is admittedly not as clean to analyze as =
a SaaS model. Selling sticky, high-margin software is good business if you =
can get it, but in many legacy, physical-world industries, software isn=E2=
=80=99t the lever on progress that a vertically-integrated business can be.=
 Fortunately for Earth AI, by being forced to pivot away from SaaS, I think=
 they discovered a much more cash-generative business model, one that looks=
 a lot like a biotech platform.=C2=A0
Last weekend, Elliot wrote an excellent piece on biotech platforms that he =
titled Compounding Until Inflection [ https://substack.com/redirect/c86dee0=
9-d278-4179-a68d-03f416876d61?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlX=
XepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ].=C2=A0
=E2=80=9CAll value comes from clinical products,=E2=80=9D he writes, =E2=80=
=9CBut it=E2=80=99s only possible to build a generational biotech company w=
ith a foundational technology platform capable of developing multiple produ=
cts.=E2=80=9D Within platforms, the biotech companies that have held onto t=
heir assets instead of partnering them away to big pharma have performed be=
tter in the market to date, but Elliot argues that platform companies whose=
 value compounds with more data can actually benefit from partnering in the=
 long-term.=C2=A0
The logic goes like this:=C2=A0
Partnerships =E2=80=93 in which a platform sells a piece of its drug to a l=
arge pharma company and develops it with them =E2=80=93 cap upside but gene=
rate short-term cash flow and data.=C2=A0
The cash allows the platform to a) survive and b) explore more assets.=C2=
=A0
The data allows the platform to improve the core technology and increase th=
e odds of spitting off more and better assets in the future.=C2=A0
As the platform builds up a warchest and its technology via partnerships, i=
t reaches a point at which it can develop more valuable programs in the fut=
ure, fund their development, and retain ownership, creating more long-term =
value for the business.=C2=A0
The platform gets paid to compound until it hits an inflection point.=C2=A0
I see a lot of similarities between that model and what Earth AI is doing.=
=C2=A0
Earth AI=E2=80=99s Business Model
Like any platform biotech company, Earth AI has developed technology that i=
t uses to discover and validate new assets better than incumbents can. Toda=
y, it can monetize those assets in a couple of main ways:
Ownership: Earth AI can own and develop assets until they=E2=80=99re valuab=
le to sell. For now, this could be as early as mid-feasibility (~ 20% stake=
 for $10M) or as late as post-feasibility (~ 80% stake for $400M - $2B).=C2=
=A0
Exploration Alliances: Like a pharma partnership, partner explorers cover E=
arth AI=E2=80=99s costs, and Earth AI receives a 2-3% royalty. Earth AI is =
paid to learn, and receives pure margin cash flows when they=E2=80=99re suc=
cessful. The partner can choose to buy 1% of its royalty back for $2.5M wit=
hin one year of discovery.=C2=A0
Today, Earth AI is pursuing both models. Exploration Alliance partners are =
essentially paying for the company to learn, collect data, and refine the d=
iscover/drill process that is its core IP. At Willow Glen, the company is f=
unding its own drilling costs in exchange for more ownership, and with each=
 successful drill, the value it can capture from a downstream developer or =
producer increases.=C2=A0
Like pharma, the cash flows from the assets that Earth AI discovers are pro=
tected =E2=80=93 in the case of pharma, by patents, and in the case of Eart=
h AI, by mineral rights granted by the state. Once it discovers a deposit, =
it owns the deposit, and can either generate revenue from it or sell its ri=
ghts to a larger player. Unlike SaaS, a competitor can=E2=80=99t simply plo=
p down on one of its existing sites and try to outcompete it.=C2=A0
Over time, Earth AI will build up a portfolio of revenue streams in additio=
n to chunky cash payments while growing its data set and getting more reps =
on its discover/drill process. It can reinvest the cash it generates into m=
ore drilling rigs, which will allow it to crank the machine more quickly, a=
nd into owning more wholly-owned projects that it can carry further through=
 the development process. Eventually, it may even attempt to use its growin=
g balance sheet to mine its own deposits.=C2=A0
Right now, all of this cash generation lives in the future. I believe that =
Earth AI is in a critical two-year period during which the key constraint w=
ill be capital.=C2=A0
If a single-asset biotech fails Phase I trials, the company is essentially =
dead. If Earth AI fails feasibility at Willow Glen, it will be a setback bu=
t not a deathblow given its live Exploration Alliances and ability to disco=
ver new deposits, assuming it has the capital to do so. Given the three suc=
cessful drills, failing feasibility seems unlikely, but feasibility takes t=
ime. (And even unsuccessful deposits can be sold for $1-5 million, recoupin=
g costs).
But capital is important, because capital buys speed.=C2=A0
With more capital, Earth AI can buy more drills, speed up feasibility at Wi=
llow Glen, begin drilling new targets, and expand its footprint to new depo=
sits while it awaits results. Without it, it will be a waiting game. But in=
 either case, given that the company may be able to sell a stake in the pro=
ject mid-feasibility, Earth AI should still be able to spin the machine, it=
=E2=80=99s just a matter of pace.=C2=A0
I=E2=80=99ve tried to construct a case in which Earth AI just fails, but gi=
ven their recent progress and the number of options they have, it seems unl=
ikely. Of course, there=E2=80=99s always that possibility. The biggest exis=
tential threats might be that commodities markets sag, making developers an=
d producers less likely to acquire mines, that Earth AI isn=E2=80=99t able =
to successfully navigate the sales process, or that all of the positive ear=
ly results happened to be flukes. They still need to be proven feasible.=C2=
=A0
But the more I dig into the business, the more excited I get. The downside =
seems protected and the upside, well, let=E2=80=99s look at the numbers.=C2=
=A0
Earth AI by the Numbers
Earlier, I gave a simplified business formula for Earth AI:
# Discoveries x Success Rate x Present Value of Mine - # Discoveries x Cost=
 to Prove =3D Profit
We=E2=80=99re going to get a little bit more detailed here. I spoke with Ea=
rth AI=E2=80=99s new CFO Monte Hackett, a former industrials investment ban=
ker who had angel invested in Earth AI and got so excited by the company th=
at he recently decided to join full-time (for all equity and no cash, no le=
ss!), to get more granular on the model. Let=E2=80=99s take it step-by-step=
=2E=C2=A0
Discovering a Feasible Mine
Today, Earth AI has a 75% success rate, which is absurd compared to 0.5% in=
dustry average. But they haven=E2=80=99t proven feasibility yet, and over t=
he past decade, the conversion from discovery to success in Australia has b=
een 21.6%. That implies a 16% feasibility success rate for Earth AI. Let=E2=
=80=99s write off some early success to luck, and assume that it takes Eart=
h AI 10 attempts to discover one feasible mine.=C2=A0
At a cost of $500k per attempt, that costs $5 million.
Of those 10 attempts, let=E2=80=99s say half are total busts. That=E2=80=99=
s about right: 54.8% of Australian discoveries didn=E2=80=99t make it to th=
e resource definition stage. Write those off as $0s.=C2=A0
For the remaining 5, assume two don=E2=80=99t show enough resources to be e=
conomical today. Earth AI can sell these for $1 million apiece to companies=
 that want to hold the sites in case conditions change (prices skyrocket, t=
echnology improves) such that the mines become economical in the future. So=
 Earth AI=E2=80=99s net cost is $3 million.
Of the remaining three that make it through resource definition, Earth AI p=
ays $2 million each for resource definition. It decides to sell two to deve=
lopers mid-feasibility for $25 million each, and spend $10 million for full=
 feasibility on the third. At this stage, Earth AI nets a $34 million profi=
t.=C2=A0
All in, over roughly three years, Earth AI has made $31 million in profit a=
nd is left with one feasible deposit.
Turning the Feasible Deposit into a Mine
Feasible deposits can be worth somewhere from $500 million to $2.5 billion,=
 and more if it=E2=80=99s a really big one. Let=E2=80=99s assume that this =
deposit is at the lower end: $1 billion.
Earth AI sells an 80% stake in the mine for $800 million, which nets the co=
mpany $640 million after taxes, netting $671 in profit on the $21 million i=
nvested.
Crucially, it retains a 20% ownership, which means it will have to pay 20% =
of construction costs on the mine, and will receive 20% of the cash flows a=
s long as the mine operates.=C2=A0
In data on 98 mines that Monte pulled, the median mine generates $430 milli=
on in annual revenue for 25 years, so let=E2=80=99s go with that. At a 40% =
cash flow margin, Earth AI would receive $34 million in EBITDA per year fro=
m the mine as long as it operates.
If the mine costs $500 million to construct, Earth AI has to pay $100 milli=
on. It does that by securitizing the cash flows from the mine at an interes=
t expense of $4 million per year.
Cash Flow from the Mine
Earth AI receives $34 million in EBITDA (earnings before interest, taxes, d=
epreciation, and amortization) from the mine per year. It has to pay $4 mil=
lion in interest, for an EBT (earnings before taxes) of $30 million per yea=
r. At a 30% tax rate, it will pay $9 million in taxes per year.=C2=A0
That means that each year, for as long as the mine operates, Earth AI will =
earn $21 million in net cash flow from the mine.=C2=A0
At a conservative assumption of 30 years of operation and an 8% discount ra=
te, the present value of those future cash flows is $150 million.
Taking into consideration the present value of the costs Earth AI paid upfr=
ont, the small sales it made, and $640 million it received from the sale of=
 the 80% stake, the total present value to Earth AI is $642 million.=C2=A0
Valuing the Mine
There are a lot of public mining companies, most listed in Australia and Ca=
nada. If Earth AI were to go public based on the illustrative mine above, w=
hat might it be worth?=C2=A0
We ran some scenarios based on the $34 million EBITDA number with various E=
BITDA multiples and values of the mine when Earth AI sells its 80% stake to=
 come up to come up with a range of values based on one mine:=C2=A0
The outcomes range from $392 million in the worst case scenario, to $1.8 bi=
llion in the best case scenario. (Franco Nevada, the best-case comp, is a p=
ublicly traded royalty bank that buys royalties in mines and may be a bette=
r comp than a traditional miner given that Earth AI=E2=80=99s value will be=
 from royalties.)
These numbers are not meant to be precise, but to illustrate the kind of va=
lue that Earth AI might be able to generate if it=E2=80=99s able to prove f=
easibility on a deposit and find a buyer willing to pay market price for ju=
st one deposit. It shows that this can be a valuable business with even one=
 successful deposit.=C2=A0
Valuing Earth AI=C2=A0
The point of Earth AI, though, is to find many deposits, not just one. Inst=
ead of sitting on cash, Earth AI will use it to build more MLD systems, whi=
ch can be used to make more discoveries and prove out more feasible mines, =
in a repeating cycle.=C2=A0
The $640 million from an 80% sale would be able to fund over 1,000 drilling=
 attempts, which at the same 1-in-10 success rate we assumed above, could y=
ield over 100 feasible mines (which, in turn, would fund more MLD systems, =
or allow Earth AI to move further up the mining stack or return cash to sha=
reholders). Even assuming they get 10x worse, 10 feasible mines would be a =
bonanza.=C2=A0
A simple way to think about how to value Earth AI is to think about how man=
y feasible mines they might be able to develop, and, using the same numbers=
 above, multiply the outcomes by the number of mines.=C2=A0
At three mines, the company might be worth $1.2 to $5.5 billion.=C2=A0
At ten mines, it might be worth $3.9 to $18.2 billion. Taking the midpoint =
of the range, it would take 90 mines to create a $100 billion company, not =
far off from Roman=E2=80=99s goal of building a $100 billion mining company=
 by finding 100 new metal deposits by the end of the decade.=C2=A0
Please note that these are rough illustrations and not precise projections.=
 Obviously, a lot has to go right to get from here to there, and the end of=
 the decade is an absurdly aggressive timeline for a process that takes so =
much time, even if Earth AI manages to speed it up dramatically.=C2=A0
But with thousands of operational mines in the world, thousands of explorer=
s working relatively inefficiently to discover new deeposits, and a rapidly=
 growing demand for critical metals, it=E2=80=99s possible to imagine a wor=
ld in which Earth AI becomes something like the supplier-of-choice to large=
 miners, exploring, drilling, and selling new projects for their consumptio=
n.=C2=A0
Another way to think about it is that BHP=E2=80=99s ~$150bn market cap is s=
upported by roughly 30 mines at a 6.9x EV/EBITDA ratio. By comparison, thin=
k about how Earth AI=E2=80=99s 20% cash flow stake in a similar number of m=
ines, without the cost or logistical burden of operating them, might be val=
ued. Not to mention the massive upfront cash distributions on 30 mines at $=
300 - $900 million per mine, which the company can put back to work in disc=
overing new promising sites.=C2=A0
That begs the question: won=E2=80=99t everyone just do this?=C2=A0
Digging Moats=C2=A0
The glib answer to the question is that it won=E2=80=99t matter if they do.=
 There are a lot of valuable deposits left to be discovered and mined. The =
longer answer is that Earth AI has built a system that allows it to find an=
d prove those deposits more quickly than anyone in a way that would take sa=
crifice for others to copy. By the time they do, Earth AI may be sitting on=
 a large portfolio=C2=A0 of profitable mine stakes.=C2=A0
I love strategy and moats more than the next guy. I wrote two pieces =E2=80=
=93 When to Dig a Moat [ https://substack.com/redirect/ebb72162-71ed-47a7-9=
de3-0a1e13cb90f2?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m=
8ExkRNpU ] and In Defense of Strategy [ https://substack.com/redirect/bb469=
e99-e46d-4a7b-8fb6-023aeb337ff0?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjm=
lXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] - arguing that it=E2=80=99s a bad idea to just ex=
ecute really hard and fast without taking the time to set your strategy and=
 figure out what moats you=E2=80=99re digging.=C2=A0
Having said that, I think that Earth AI is now in a position in which they =
just need to move really fast. Raise capital, invest in MLD systems, stake =
claim to promising deposits, and drill them as quickly as possible.=C2=A0
The reason is the structure of the mining industry: once an explorer stakes=
 a deposit, it=E2=80=99s theirs. There are thousands of deposits waiting to=
 be staked around the world, and with early signs of success from both the =
Mineral Targeting Platform and MLD system, Earth AI is in a good position t=
o capitalize on the opportunity.=C2=A0
Importantly, Earth AI can move fast because it knows which moats it can dig=
: cornered resource, process power, and counter-positioning.
According to 7 Powers author Hamilton Helmer, a cornered resource is prefer=
ential access at attractive terms to an asset that can independently increa=
se value. In the case of Earth AI, the cornered resources are the mineral r=
ights it acquires when it stakes a deposit. In countries with stable politi=
cal regimes, like Australia, mineral rights are a license to print money if=
 it turns out that the deposit is economically feasible. It costs money and=
 risk to acquire these rights, and prove feasibility, but once Earth AI own=
s the rights, no competitor can take that site from them.=C2=A0
Because mines are like businesses in themselves =E2=80=93 with many generat=
ing upwards of $1 billion per year in revenue =E2=80=93 Earth AI has a corn=
ered resource in each one of its mines. In the example above, once it prove=
s feasibility on its mine and sells a stake, it could fire everyone except =
for an accountant to count all of the $34 million coming in every year for =
as long as the mine bears fruit.=C2=A0
But again, that=E2=80=99s not the goal. The goal is 100 mines. That=E2=80=
=99s where the second moat =E2=80=93 process power =E2=80=93 comes in.=C2=
=A0
Process power is the most ineffable of the seven. It=E2=80=99s the embedded=
 sets of company organization and activity which enable lower cost and/or s=
uperior product. Like Toyota=E2=80=99s Total Production System, it=E2=80=99=
s something that, even if you trained outsiders on it, they wouldn=E2=80=99=
t be able to copy precisely to do the same thing you do.=C2=A0
In Earth AI=E2=80=99s case, the process power comes from the fact that it=
=E2=80=99s not just an AI company, not just a team of geologists, and not j=
ust a high-volume driller, but all three at once. By doing 80 pilots for ex=
plorers, then testing 132 sites, then building its own drilling rig from sc=
ratch and evolving the system based on on-the-ground needs, Earth AI has ea=
rned valuable tacit knowledge that would take time and experience to match.=
=C2=A0
They=E2=80=99ve taken that tacit knowledge and built it into a system that =
fits together in a way that serves their very specific needs: high-volume, =
surgically-precise exploration and drilling is a different game than most i=
n the industry play, and as a result, Earth AI is developing a different se=
t of skills.=C2=A0
If you had 6,000 targets but relied on contractors to drill them, it would =
take centuries to go through them all. If you had the fastest drilling rig =
in the world, but you were set up to make one discovery, that drill rig=E2=
=80=99s value would be limited. And as Earth AI=E2=80=99s attempts to sell =
software to explorers proved, put great data in the hands of traditional ex=
plorers and they won=E2=80=99t find a use for it. Earth AI=E2=80=99s proces=
s power comes from fitting together those pieces: it can find a lot of prom=
ising deposits and prove them quickly, building more knowledge with each fa=
ilure and success, and continue to add more MLD systems to speed up its pro=
cess and knowledge acquisition.=C2=A0
The fact that it has the opportunity to grow this lead comes down to counte=
r-positioning.
As Ian Rountree of Cantos, an Earth AI investor and board member, explained=
 to me, drillers can=E2=80=99t do exploration alliances for more valuable r=
oyalty streams because they=E2=80=99re low-margin fee-for-service businesse=
s. Earth AI can.
Explorers can=E2=80=99t invest in technology systems or better drilling rig=
s because they can=E2=80=99t amortize those costs across as many discoverie=
s. Earth AI can.=C2=A0
And even large miners don=E2=80=99t want to move down into the exploration =
phase because their core competency is in acquiring and mining deposits. Ju=
st like pharma companies, they=E2=80=99ve outsourced =E2=80=9Cinnovation=E2=
=80=9D to smaller players. Where they do use technology like Earth AI=E2=80=
=99s, it=E2=80=99s in discovering more deposits at existing minesites where=
 they=E2=80=99re already established in order to increase those sites=E2=80=
=99 profitability. Plus, they=E2=80=99re not exactly incentivized to suppor=
t new discoveries: they already have cornered resources, and the biggest th=
reat to their margins is a glut of competitive supply.=C2=A0
You can see this in the data. The share of exploration budget going to gras=
sroots exploration has been cut in half since 1997, from 50% to 23%, even a=
s exploration budgets in general have shrunk from a peak of $21 billion in =
2012 to $12.8 billion last year, per S&P Global [ https://substack.com/redi=
rect/904d3f79-5f4a-47a0-8cae-12d9760b394b?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA=
_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]. Remaining budgets have shifted to late=
 stage & feasibility =E2=80=93 proving out deposits that have been discover=
ed =E2=80=93 and minesite - discovering additional mineral resources on exi=
sting sites to extend the life of the mine, increase production, or improve=
 the mine=E2=80=99s overall economics.=C2=A0
Earth AI is making a counter-positioned bet that there=E2=80=99s a lot of v=
alue left to be discovered in the grassroots, greenfield discovery with bet=
ter technology. Whether it=E2=80=99s right, and whether the company can con=
vince miners to acquire its deposits if it is, will determine whether or no=
t this is a multi-billion dollar outcome.=C2=A0
To summarize, Earth AI=E2=80=99s counter-positioning gives it a head start,=
 which it can use to acquire cornered cash flowing resources and continue t=
o develop process power, which it can use to discover and prove out deposit=
s more quickly than others in the industry.=C2=A0
But critical metals discovery is not a winner-take-all market. Earth AI won=
=E2=80=99t make all of the discoveries, even in Australia. We=E2=80=99ll ne=
ed a dozen smart companies working on the problem if we=E2=80=99re going to=
 address the world=E2=80=99s demand for critical metals, of which quasi-com=
petitor KoBold Metals [ https://substack.com/redirect/15703578-7bab-487e-94=
04-7d21e8536028?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8=
ExkRNpU ] says, =E2=80=9CThe industry needs to discover more than twelve tr=
illion dollars worth of new critical mineral deposits to stop catastrophic =
climate change.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0
The good news is, Earth AI has a number of quasi-competitors / quasi-allies=
 in the search for more critical metals like KoBold.=C2=A0
Quasi-Competitors=C2=A0
In November, The Economist wrote a piece titled Could AI help find valuable=
 minerals? [ https://substack.com/redirect/a76b870d-28c0-4c61-8f0b-24e984fc=
2557?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] i=
n which they mentioned Earth AI alongside other companies using AI for disc=
overy, including KoBold, SensOre, OreFox, VerAI, and even Rio Tinto.=C2=A0
Great times, then, for prospectors, and particularly for any who think they=
 can increase the efficiency of their profession. Several firms are applyin=
g artificial intelligence [ https://substack.com/redirect/8eddd0d8-e259-4f6=
6-bf44-f3f7ef525ca2?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8=
-6m8ExkRNpU ] (ai) to the process, both to improve the odds of surface stri=
kes and to detect underground ore bodies that are invisible to current tech=
niques.
The article paints the companies with a similar brush =E2=80=93 AI! =E2=80=
=93 but they=E2=80=99re taking subtly, but importantly, different approache=
s.=C2=A0
Both OreFox and SensOre pursued the Earth AI 1.0 model =E2=80=93 trying to =
sell software to explorers to improve their mining efforts. That is a chall=
enging business. The larger of the two, SensOre, is public on the ASX; its =
