=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0=
 20px 0;">The Vladistovokan bears were built different: hungry (no arctic r=
ivers full of salmon) and therefore angry. &#8220;I had a shotgun in the tu=
ndra, but not in Vladivostok, which turned out to be a problem,&#8221; Roma=
n recounted. &#8220;I had to literally run away from a bear who tried to at=
tack us. The story is&#8230;&#8221;</p><blockquote style=3D"border-left: 4p=
x solid #51b4e9; margin: 20px 0; padding: 0;"><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55=
, 55); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0; margin-left:=
 20px;"><em>I was sampling soil on a E-W line with a local field assistant.=
 A bloke of 40 years of age from a nearby village who, as it turned out, ha=
d never seen a bear. I had seen many in the tundra and had two close encoun=
ters, when solo mapping geology 5-10 miles away from the mine. In one case,=
 I just had to step back one step and we went different ways; the other, I =
fired a few shots in the air and that made the bear go away. But not this t=
ime.&#160;</em></p><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; lin=
e-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0; margin-left: 20px;"><em>We were walking=
 back to camp in heavy downpour through the forest when I faced the bear 20=
 feet away from me. I guess the rain was too loud for it to hear us. Three =
problems. First, we didn't have a gun or any bear deterrent devices; second=
, my usual method of stopping and taking one step back to show that I didn&=
#8217;t want any trouble was completely ignored by the bear who started app=
roaching us; and finally, the local assistant that I had, seeing a bear for=
 the first time in his entire life, first froze, and then, when the bear ro=
ared, started running away..doing exactly what they say not to do in the te=
xtbooks!</em></p><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-=
height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0; margin-left: 20px;"><em>So that left me i=
n between the running man and the bear who decided to chase him. I had no h=
ope, but decided to run too, knowing that I was indeed the slower one with =
a larger backpack full of samples...I was waiting for the &quot;tap on the =
shoulder.&quot;&#160;</em></p><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size=
: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0; margin-left: 20px;"><em><spa=
n>And then, the luckiest thing happened. </span><strong>I hit a tree with m=
y backpack,with such force that my straps &quot;ejected&quot; and I broke f=
ree from the weight and could run faster.</strong><span> I never looked bac=
k and never wondered what happened to the bear: did the backpack stop him? =
or did he just want to scare us away? No one will ever know.&#160;</span></=
em></p></blockquote><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; li=
ne-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">Your CEO could never&#8230; Anyway, V=
ladivostok was beautiful, but after a year in the forest, Roman decided he =
wanted to advance, and not just practice, geology. It was time to get his P=
hD. He &#8220;applied to 100 places, twice&#8221; before getting into Sydne=
y University, home to one of the top geology programs in the world, on a fu=
ll scholarship.&#160;</p><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16p=
x; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">This was it. From humble beginni=
ngs in Ukraine, to the tundras of Kamchatka and the forests of Vladivostok,=
 Roman was finally getting to do research on the cutting edge of geology in=
 a warm, western country!&#160;</p><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font=
-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">The thing was, when he=
 got there, the research was deeply unsatisfying. He quickly realized that =
the work they were doing wasn&#8217;t solving any fundamental problems in g=
eology, like how to better identify new deposits. Instead, they were applyi=
ng traditional tools to describe the same old rocks.&#160;</p><p style=3D"c=
olor: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px=
 0;"><span>Roman wanted to figure out how to do it better, so he read a ton=
 of papers, manually sifted through reams of data. As he did, he came to a =
troubling realization: </span><strong>geology as practiced wasn&#8217;t rea=
lly a science</strong><span>.&#160;</span></p><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55=
, 55); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;"><span>Two p=
apers with the same data on the same rock formation would propose two total=
ly different and contradictory theories. They were </span><em>opinions</em>=
<span> that neglected the data. &#8220;When you have two contradictory pape=
rs on the same data set,&#8221; he told me, &#8220;the science stops being =
science.&#8221; Even worse, it was political. He couldn&#8217;t even choose=
 which theory he agreed with based on the data; he had to quote the one tha=
t his advisor allied with. &#8220;If you already know what the party line i=
s,&#8221; he asked, &#8220;why even do the research?&#8221;&#160;</span></p=
><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; ma=
rgin: 0 0 20px 0;"><span>He hadn&#8217;t roamed the Kamchatka tundra with a=
 shotgun, braved the Vladistovokan forests </span><em>without </em><span>a =
shotgun, and moved halfway around the world to play politics. The man just =
loved the rocks, and he wanted to understand what they were trying to tell =
him. So he started pulling all of the publicly available data &#8211; which=
 is around 400 million data points in Australia&#8217;s open records alone =
&#8211; taught himself data science, and built something in a &#8220;half-a=
utomated way&#8221; that reclassified rocks based purely on all of the data=
 available.&#160;</span></p><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: =
16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;"><span>If you&#8217;ve ever wo=
rked on a project like that &#8211; built a model, built a product, built a=
 website, whatever &#8211; that finally starts producing real results after=
 months of toil, you understand the excitement Roman felt. This could chang=
e geology! Unfortunately, though, it couldn&#8217;t change </span><em>geolo=
gists</em><span>.&#160;</span></p><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-=
size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">When he presented his f=
indings to his department, they told him, &#8220;This might be interesting =
to some of the computer people, but it&#8217;s not interesting to us.&#8221=
;&#160;</p><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-height=
: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">At that point, Roman came to the same realizat=
ion that thousands of unintentional entrepreneurs have come to: if he wante=
d to actually change how things worked, he was going to have to start a com=
pany.&#160;</p><h3 class=3D"header-with-anchor-widget" style=3D"-moz-appear=
ance: optimizelegibility; -moz-osx-font-smoothing: antialiased; -webkit-app=
earance: optimizelegibility; -webkit-font-smoothing: antialiased; appearanc=
e: optimizelegibility; color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-family: 'SF Pro Display=
