: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;"=
>And it actually worked. He went through the list alphabetically, and got h=
is first hit while he was still in the A&#8217;s - ActivEX. He offered a fr=
ee trial, after which they&#8217;d pay $3k per month, and they actually con=
verted!&#160;</p><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-=
height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">Fueled by the early success and inspired=
 by Elon&#8217;s work at Tesla and SpaceX, Roman decided it was time to dro=
p out and go all in on this thing. He raised $600k from AirTree Ventures an=
d Blackbird Ventures, two of the top early stage venture funds down under, =
and transitioned his visa from research to business. Fun fact: Roman receiv=
ed the first entrepreneur visa in Australian history.&#160;</p><p style=3D"=
color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20p=
x 0;">Over four months, Earth AI hired a team of data scientists and ran 80=
 pilots for customers, an insane pace that left little room for sleep but p=
roduced a ton of learning very quickly.&#160;</p><p style=3D"color: rgb(54,=
 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;"><span>Th=
e biggest lesson was this: </span><strong>software was not the right model =
for this business</strong><span>.&#160;</span></p><p style=3D"color: rgb(54=
, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">The ind=
ustry moved too slowly, the sales cycle was too long, and it simply wasn&#8=
217;t a big enough market to build a really big software business. Some com=
panies paid as much as $50k for the analysis, which was great, but it wasn&=
#8217;t repeatable. And what&#8217;s worse was that, even though they paid =
good money, most didn&#8217;t actually put the analysis to work. Only four =
of the 80 pilot companies actually went out and sampled the sites, and thos=
e after weeks or months of Roman&#8217;s prodding. All of which meant that =
Roman didn&#8217;t know if the analysis actually worked!&#160;</p><p style=
=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0=
 20px 0;">Alright, so if it wasn&#8217;t a software business, what if they =
moved to the next level of the stack and actually went out and did the samp=
ling themselves?&#160;</p><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16=
px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">That&#8217;s what they did. Bou=
ght a truck, went out in the field, surveyed, sampled, and delivered sample=
s to customers. And once again, the customers said, &#8220;Thanks&#8221; an=
d then &#8220;goodbye.&#8221; They treated Earth AI as a surveying company,=
 and had no intentions of keeping their surveyor abreast of any further dev=
elopments.&#160;</p><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; li=
ne-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">Roman summed up what they&#8217;d lea=
rned:</p><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-height: =
26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">&#8220;Software provider: shitty, not a valued b=
usiness.&#160;</p><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line=
-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">Surveying contractor: shitty, not a val=
ued business.&#8221;&#160;</p><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size=
: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">Up next: &#8220;Let&#8217;s=
 go out ourselves and test our system to prove that it works.&#8221;</p><p =
style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin=
: 0 0 20px 0;">It was a risky move. He&#8217;d spent $200-300k of the origi=
nal $600k, then raised another $800k. But the company felt like it was perp=
etually running out of cash, and digging wasn&#8217;t what the data scienti=
sts had signed up for. Some quit, the rest Roman fired.&#160;</p><p style=
=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0=
 20px 0;">Earth AI went down to two people, then hired Isabella Sykes, a Un=
iversity of Sydney geology student who&#8217;s now the company&#8217;s COO.=
 Then they hired more geology students, put together all the gear they&#821=
7;d need to go out and test their sites, and got out there, with Alice Spri=
ngs in the Northern Territory, smack dab in the middle of the country, as t=
he base camp.&#160;</p><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px;=
 line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;"><span>Over the next six months, th=
e small team of geologists </span><strong>tested 132 sites</strong><span>. =
Two geologists would take the gear-loaded car out from Alice Springs into t=
he desert for two weeks at a time, survey, and bring back what they found t=
o analyze while another team of two hopped in the car out to the desert for=
 another two-week stint. Non-stop, for six months. It was exhausting work, =
but it worked!&#160;</span></p><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-siz=
e: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">&#8220;We found 35 brand n=
ew prospects with mineralization that hadn&#8217;t been found before,&#8221=
; Roman told me. &#8220;We went to an area with no historical data, predict=
ed new prospects, and found them.&#8221;&#160;</p><p style=3D"color: rgb(54=
, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">&#8220;=
Holy shit we&#8217;ve gotta stake all of this,&#8221; he added. So Earth AI=
 staked 9 exploration licenses with the government, giving the company the =
rights to whatever they dug up for as long as they could dig.&#160;</p><p s=
tyle=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin:=
 0 0 20px 0;">Surveying, though, is just step one in the process. You&#8217=
;re essentially mapping the area, seeing mineralization that suggests there=
 might be deposits beneath the surface. To produce any real value, you&#821=
7;ve got to drill.&#160;</p><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: =
16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">Traditionally, the way you&#8=
217;d do that is to hire drilling contractors. But drilling contractors are=
 slow &#8211; it can take them 6 months to get set up and drill the holes &=
#8211; and expensive &#8211; around half a million dollars. That wouldn&#82=
17;t work. Earth AI had neither the time nor the cash.&#160;</p><p style=3D=
"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20=
px 0;">So in parallel, the company did two things: tried to raise money and=
 built its own drilling rig.&#160;</p><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); f=
ont-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">First, the money. R=
oman flew out to Silicon Valley three times in five months. He met a lot of=
 people and raised nothing. Finally, on the third trip, Taver Capital gave =
the company a convertible note. Then they applied to Y Combinator, and got =
in! After that, everything changed. In 2019, Earth AI raised $3 million dol=
lars from funds including Taver Capital, Fifty Years, and Cantos.&#160;</p>=
<p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; mar=
gin: 0 0 20px 0;">Then, the drill. Roman searched around for something chea=
p, found an abandoned rig for $30k, flew to the site to check it out, confi=
rmed that it did indeed look like a drill rig, and bought it.&#160;</p><div=
 class=3D"captioned-image-container-static" style=3D"font-size: 16px; line-=
