cess Rate x Present Value of Mine - # Discoveries x Cost to Prove =3D Profi=
t</strong></code></pre><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px;=
 line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">We&#8217;re going to get a little =
bit more detailed here. I spoke with Earth AI&#8217;s new CFO Monte Hackett=
, a former industrials investment banker who had angel invested in Earth AI=
 and got so excited by the company that he recently decided to join full-ti=
me (for all equity and no cash, no less!), to get more granular on the mode=
l. Let&#8217;s take it step-by-step.&#160;</p><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55=
, 55); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;"><strong>Dis=
covering a Feasible Mine</strong></p><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); fo=
nt-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">Today, Earth AI has =
a 75% success rate, which is absurd compared to 0.5% industry average. But =
they haven&#8217;t proven feasibility yet, and over the past decade, the co=
nversion from discovery to success in Australia has been 21.6%. That implie=
s a 16% feasibility success rate for Earth AI. Let&#8217;s write off some e=
arly success to luck, and assume that it takes Earth AI 10 attempts to disc=
over one feasible mine.&#160;</p><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-s=
ize: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;"><span>At a cost of $500k=
 per attempt, that </span><strong>costs $5 million</strong><span>.</span></=
p><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; m=
argin: 0 0 20px 0;">Of those 10 attempts, let&#8217;s say half are total bu=
sts. That&#8217;s about right: 54.8% of Australian discoveries didn&#8217;t=
 make it to the resource definition stage. Write those off as $0s.&#160;</p=
><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; ma=
rgin: 0 0 20px 0;"><span>For the remaining 5, assume two don&#8217;t show e=
nough resources to be economical today. Earth AI can sell these for $1 mill=
ion apiece to companies that want to hold the sites in case conditions chan=
ge (prices skyrocket, technology improves) such that the mines become econo=
mical in the future. So Earth AI&#8217;s </span><strong>net cost is $3 mill=
ion</strong><span>.</span></p><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size=
: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;"><span>Of the remaining thre=
e that make it through resource definition, Earth AI pays $2 million each f=
or resource definition. It decides to sell two to developers mid-feasibilit=
y for $25 million each, and spend $10 million for full feasibility on the t=
hird. At this stage, Earth AI nets a </span><strong>$34 million profit</str=
ong><span>.&#160;</span></p><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: =
16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;"><span>All in, over roughly th=
ree years, </span><strong>Earth AI has made $31 million in profit and is le=
ft with one feasible deposit</strong><span>.</span></p><p style=3D"color: r=
gb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;"><s=
trong>Turning the Feasible Deposit into a Mine</strong></p><p style=3D"colo=
r: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;=
"><span>Feasible deposits can be worth somewhere from $500 million to $2.5 =
billion, and more if it&#8217;s a really big one. Let&#8217;s assume that t=
his deposit is at the lower end: </span><strong>$1 billion.</strong></p><p =
style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin=
: 0 0 20px 0;"><span>Earth AI sells an 80% stake in the mine for $800 milli=
on, which nets the company </span><strong>$640 million after taxes</strong>=
<span>, netting </span><strong>$671 in profit</strong><span> on the $21 mil=
lion invested.</span></p><div class=3D"captioned-image-container-static" st=
yle=3D"font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 32px auto;"><figure styl=
